{"source_key":"sha256-9aeddc9533856b773c893728ead17d15","record_index":5,"record_hash":"sha256:d8445f5f21d39d798e1464f8172499e9bc76106052f2a91639049efc804c6b07","timestamp":"2026-05-13T13:17:53.327Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"In crates/gitbutler-git/src/context.rs we are constructing a refspec like this `let refspec = format!(\"+refs/heads/*:refs/remotes/{remote_name}/*\");`\n\nThe problem is that while this is often correct, in some cases the spec is different. For example i have this in my git config:\n```\n[remote \"origin\"]\n\turl = git@github.com:gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\n\tfetch = +refs/heads/*:refs/remotes/origin/*\n[remote \"meta\"]\n\turl = git@github.com:gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\n    fetch = +refs/meta/main:refs/meta/remote/main\n\tmeta = true\n\tpromisor = true\n\tpartialclonefilter = blob:none\n```\n\nSo the refspec we build would be correct for the origin remote but incorrect for the meta remote. \n\nMy question is, given a remote name, can we use gix / gitoxide to obtain the correct fetch spec?\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-13T13:17:53.327Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}